// validation :- checking data formats, types, required fields etc
// authentication :- checking if user is who they say they are
// authorization :- checking if user has permission to access a resource
// Varification :- checking if user has access to a resource by verifying their credentials

// Token :- a string of characters that is used to verify the identity of a user and their permissions. It is usually generated by the server and sent to the client after successful authentication. The client then includes this token in subsequent requests to access protected resources. The server verifies the token to ensure that the user is authenticated and authorized to access the requested resource.

// JWT (JSON Web Token) :- a type of token that is used for authentication and authorization. It is a compact, URL-safe string that contains a JSON object with claims about the user and their permissions. The JWT is signed using a secret key or a public/private key pair, which allows the server to verify its authenticity and integrity. JWTs are commonly used in modern web applications for stateless authentication and authorization.

// Token-based authentication :- a method of authentication where the server generates a token after successful authentication and sends it to the client. The client then includes this token in subsequent requests to access protected resources. The server verifies the token to ensure that the user is authenticated and authorized to access the requested resource. This method is stateless, meaning that the server does not need to maintain any session information about the user, as all the necessary information is contained in the token itself.

// JWT-based authentication :- a specific implementation of token-based authentication that uses JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) as the token format. In this method, the server generates a JWT after successful authentication and sends it to the client. The client then includes this JWT in subsequent requests to access protected resources. The server verifies the JWT to ensure that the user is authenticated and authorized to access the requested resource. This method is also stateless, as all the necessary information about the user and their permissions is contained in the JWT itself.